<b>Linux-Mandrake is 99% compatible with RedHat.</b> So most applications packaged for RedHat as RPM packages (.rpm file) should run under Mandrake.<p>

Such apps can be found on: <p>

<ul>
<li> <a href="http://www.linux-mandrake.com"></a>The very well organized 'rufus.w3.org' server on <a href="http://rufus.w3.org/linux/RPM/contrib/libc6/i386/">http://rufus.w3.org/linux/RPM/contrib/libc6/i386/</a><p>
<li> The Linux Center where all application are listed <a href="http://www.linux-center.org/" target="_parent">http://www.linux-center.org</a><p>
<li> Freshmeat quickfinder on  <a href="http://news.freshmeat.net/" target="_parent">http://news.freshmeat.net/</a> that allows you to find the lastest versions.<p>
<li> AppWatch at  <a href="http://appwatch.com/linux"> http://appwatch.com/Linux</a> which does the same efficiently. You can see the latest applications on the right column.<p>
<li> Another applications source is the <a href="cookerdevel.php3">Cooker</A> from Mandrakesoft.<p>
</ul>
 
<p> Anyways, <b>try avoiding upgrading Mandrake specific packages (those that can be found in the Mandrake distribution) with RedHat's ones.</b> You could lose Mandrake's benefits.
